<div class="page">

  <div class="header">
    <div class="header-eyebrow">Instructional Design Portfolio · Case Study</div>
    <h1>Swim Science: Why Water Pushes Back</h1>
    <div class="header-subtitle">Interactive Learning Tool · Poolside Reference for Masters Swimmers and Coaches</div>
    <div class="tag-row">
      <span class="header-tag">Backward Design</span>
      <span class="header-tag">Dual Coding Theory</span>
      <span class="header-tag">Cognitive Load Theory</span>
      <span class="header-tag">Anchored Instruction</span>
      <span class="header-tag">HTML / CSS / JS</span>
      <span class="header-tag">Self-Directed Learning</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="context-strip">
    <div class="context-item">
      <span class="context-label">Audience</span>
      <span class="context-value">Masters Swimmers · Coaches</span>
    </div>
    <div class="context-item">
      <span class="context-label">Modality</span>
      <span class="context-value">Interactive Web Tool</span>
    </div>
    <div class="context-item">
      <span class="context-label">Format</span>
      <span class="context-value">Standalone HTML · Mobile-Ready</span>
    </div>
    <div class="context-item">
      <span class="context-label">Transfer Context</span>
      <span class="context-value">Pool Deck · Self-Directed Use</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="body">

    <div class="section">
      <span class="section-label">Project Overview</span>
      <p>A standalone interactive learning tool translating hydrodynamic drag theory into poolside-ready knowledge for adult swimmers and coaches. Built around one transfer goal: a swimmer who can self-diagnose and correct in real time, without an instructor present. The tool covers four interconnected drag concepts — Form Drag, Boundary Layer Separation, Active Drag, and Wave Drag — delivered through a tabbed progressive disclosure architecture, an animated body-position visualizer, and a tappable splash diagnostic checklist.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <span class="section-label">Live Tool</span>
      <div class="tool-callout">
        <div class="tool-preview">
          <div class="tool-preview-eyebrow">Swim Science</div>
          <div class="tool-preview-title">Why the Water<br><span>Pushes Back</span></div>
          <div class="tool-preview-tabs">
            <div class="tool-preview-tab active">💡 The Big Idea</div>
            <div class="tool-preview-tab">🌊 The Four Forces</div>
            <div class="tool-preview-tab">🏊 Deck Tools</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tool-preview-cards">
            <div class="tool-preview-card">
              <div class="tool-preview-card-label">Form Drag</div>
              <div class="tool-preview-card-tag">The Wall You Build</div>
            </div>
            <div class="tool-preview-card">
              <div class="tool-preview-card-label">Boundary Layer</div>
              <div class="tool-preview-card-tag">Losing the Water's Cooperation</div>
            </div>
            <div class="tool-preview-card">
              <div class="tool-preview-card-label">Active Drag</div>
              <div class="tool-preview-card-tag">The Real Number</div>
            </div>
            <div class="tool-preview-card">
              <div class="tool-preview-card-label">Wave Drag</div>
              <div class="tool-preview-card-tag">Energy Spent Going Nowhere</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tool-content">
          <div class="tool-text">
            <strong>Interactive Swim Science Reference</strong><br>
            Three-zone tabbed tool with animated body-position visualizer, expandable concept cards, tappable splash diagnostic, and poolside drill. Designed for use on a phone between sets.
          </div>
          <a class="tool-button" href="https://jamesdrodgers.ai/swim/why-water-pushes-back" target="_blank">View Live Tool</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <span class="section-label">Pedagogical Framework</span>
      <div class="principle-grid">
        <div class="principle-card">
          <div class="principle-num">01</div>
          <div class="principle-name">Dual Coding Theory</div>
          <div class="principle-desc">An animated torpedo/shopping cart visualizer encodes body position spatially before any verbal explanation appears. Every concept card pairs physics language with proprioceptive sensation. Visual and verbal channels fire simultaneously throughout.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="principle-card">
          <div class="principle-num">02</div>
          <div class="principle-name">Cognitive Load Theory</div>
          <div class="principle-desc">Three progressive tabs prevent competing concepts from loading simultaneously. Zone 1 builds the mental model. Zone 2 goes deeper. Zone 3 transfers to action. Accordion cards apply the same logic at concept level — label visible, depth on demand.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="principle-card">
          <div class="principle-num">03</div>
          <div class="principle-name">Anchored Instruction</div>
          <div class="principle-desc">Every concept is tethered to a physical sensation the swimmer has already experienced. "Swimming uphill." "The water grabs you." The physics arrives as the name for a known experience, not as unfamiliar information to memorize.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="two-col">
      <div class="section" style="margin-bottom:0">
        <span class="section-label">Design Decisions</span>
        <ul class="decision-list">
          <li><span class="del-dot"></span>Backward design from single transfer goal: poolside self-correction without instructor</li>
          <li><span class="del-dot"></span>Sensation language ("Feel It") used as primary retrieval anchor, not definition</li>
          <li><span class="del-dot"></span>Silence Drill placed before concept explanation — experience precedes taxonomy</li>
          <li><span class="del-dot"></span>Diagnostic is tappable and checkable for active mid-practice use</li>
          <li><span class="del-dot"></span>Coach-to-athlete register throughout — no academic hedging, no jargon</li>
          <li><span class="del-dot"></span>Four forces framed as one system, not an inventory</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="section" style="margin-bottom:0">
        <span class="section-label">Design Approach</span>
        <div style="display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap:10px; margin-top:4px;">
          <div class="highlight-card">
            <div class="highlight-title">Transfer-Appropriate Processing</div>
            <div class="highlight-text">Every tool is formatted for the context where learning must activate — a phone on a pool deck between sets, not a desk.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="highlight-card">
            <div class="highlight-title">Learner Autonomy</div>
            <div class="highlight-text">The diagnostic is self-administered. Video resources support independent exploration. No instructor required to use the tool effectively.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="highlight-card">
            <div class="highlight-title">4MAT Sequencing</div>
            <div class="highlight-text">Zones move through Why, What, How, and What If — ensuring every learner type finds their entry point and is pulled forward.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="artifacts-callout">
      <div class="artifacts-text">
        <strong>View the Live Tool</strong><br>
        The full interactive reference — torpedo animation, concept cards, splash diagnostic, and poolside drill — is deployed at jamesdrodgers.ai.
      </div>
      <a class="artifacts-link" href="https://jamesdrodgers.ai/swim/why-water-pushes-back" target="_blank">Open Live Tool</a>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <span class="section-label">Design Highlights</span>
      <div class="highlights-grid">
        <div class="highlight-card">
          <div class="highlight-title">Animated Body-Position Visualizer</div>
          <div class="highlight-text">An SVG animation alternates between torpedo and shopping cart body positions every 2.8 seconds, encoding the core concept visually before any text is read. Labels and sub-text shift with the animation to reinforce dual coding.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="highlight-card">
          <div class="highlight-title">Progressive Disclosure Architecture</div>
          <div class="highlight-text">Three sticky tabs manage cognitive load at the zone level. Accordion cards manage it at the concept level. Learners control depth — scanning is fast, going deep is one tap.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="highlight-card">
          <div class="highlight-title">Tappable Splash Diagnostic</div>
          <div class="highlight-text">Six checkable rows map visual/auditory cues to drag causes and fixes. Designed to be used during practice — not read after it. Tap a splash pattern, get the diagnosis and the correction immediately.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="highlight-card">
          <div class="highlight-title">Context-Calibrated Language</div>
          <div class="highlight-text">Every sentence is written for a swimmer standing on a pool deck with 90 seconds between sets. Short sentences. Active verbs. No hedging. Tone is coach-to-athlete, not textbook-to-student.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>

  <div class="footer">
    <div class="footer-name">James D. Rodgers · Instructional Designer</div>
    <div class="footer-link"><a href="https://www.jamesdrodgers.ai" target="_blank">www.jamesdrodgers.ai</a></div>
  </div>

